When you have a method that returns a boolean and has a nullable `out` parameter, it is possible to add the nullable attribute `NotNullWhen` to the `out` parameter to specify the case where it won't be `null`, depending on the value of the boolean return type.

Would it make sense to have a `NotNullWhen` attribute for return values with different data types?

For example, let's say you have a method that returns an enum that describes the result of an operation, and only on one particular case (the "success" case), the `out` parameter will not be `null`:

```cs
enum OperationResult
{
    Success,
    ErrorA,
    ErrorB
}

OperationResult TryMethod([NotNullWhen(returnValue: OperationResult.Success)] out MyType? obj)
{
    obj = null;
    if (/* Error condition A*/)
    {
        return OperationResult.ErrorA;
    }
    else if (/* Error condition B*/)
    {
        return OperationResult.ErrorB;
    }
    obj = new MyType();
    return OperationResult.Success;
}
```

Since it could also be possible to have two or more enum values that are considered "success" cases, the `NotNullWhen` attribute could take an array of values:

```cs
enum OperationResult
{
    SuccessA,
    SuccessB,
    ErrorA,
    ErrorB
}


OperationResult TryMethod(
    [NotNullWhen(returnValue: new OperationResult[] { OperationResult.SuccessA, OperationResult.SuccessB} )]
    out MyType? obj)
{
    obj = null;
    if (/* Error condition A */)
    {
        return OperationResult.ErrorA;
    }
    else if (/* Error condition B */)
    {
        return OperationResult.ErrorB;
    }
    else if (/* Success condition A */)
    {
        obj = GetMyTypeForSuccessA();
        return OperationResult.SuccessA;
    }
    else // Success condition B
    {
        obj = GetMyTypeForSuccessB();
        return OperationResult.SuccessB;
    }
}
```

This PR adds support for instance and static fields on a reference type. It interprets the following opcodes:
* `ldfld`
* `ldsfld`
* `stfld`
* `stsfld`

As a consequence of adding static field support, I also added support for interpreting static constructors on dynamically loaded types. The following scenario is now supported:

```csharp
class Class1
{
    public string Field1;
    public int Field2;
    public float Field3;

    public static string StaticField1;
    public static int StaticField2;
    public static float StaticField3;

    [ThreadStatic]
    public static int ThreadStaticField1;

    static Class1()
    {
        StaticField1 = "statically nice!";
        StaticField2 = 10;
        StaticField3 = 3.56f;
        ThreadStaticField1 = 56;
    }
}

.....

public static void DoFields()
{
    Class1 class1 = new Class1();
    class1.Field1 = "nice";
    class1.Field2 = 23;
    class1.Field3 = 2.5f;

    Console.WriteLine(class1.Field1);
    Console.WriteLine(class1.Field2);
    Console.WriteLine(class1.Field3);
}

public static void DoStaticFields()
{
    Console.WriteLine(Class1.StaticField1);
    Console.WriteLine(String.Empty);
    Console.WriteLine(Class1.StaticField2);
    Console.WriteLine(Class1.StaticField3);
    Console.WriteLine(Class1.ThreadStaticField1);
}
```

The interpreter will happily load instance and static fields on both dynamically loaded types and types compiled into the native executable, while ensuring that static constructors have been run in both cases.

